{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511090"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:37:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:37:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11698"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11698"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.02,0.02,0.62,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4313"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79139"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4313"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11698"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64491"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"1596"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7976"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8604"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26964"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42647"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79139"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents with a painless lump on his right leg (Image). This has been present for about four months. He thinks he had an insect bite in that area about six months ago, which was originally itchy and tender and he scratched it often. This lump has not altered in appearance and is not causing any discomfort.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Implantation dermoid","Plantar wart","Amelanotic melanoma","Dermatofibroma","Squamous cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical scenario and image is consistent with the diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Edermatofibroma\u003C/strong\u003E, a common benign painless a firm, raised, reddish-brown fibrous nodule usually found on the skin of the lower legs. It typically results from mild trauma such as an insect bite, injections, or a rose thorn injury. A common feature of dermatofibromas is the \u0027button sign\u0027 or \u0027dimple sign\u0027 which is typical. In lesions that are not raised essentially it is a dimpling of the skin when pinched. Multiple dermatofibromas can develop in patients with altered immunity such as HIV, immunosuppression, or autoimmune conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImplantation dermoid \u003C/strong\u003Eis an acquired condition that occurs as the result of implantation of epidermal fragments into the dermis by a penetrating injury. The epidermis continues to grow and forms a cyst lined with stratified squamous epithelium and filled with keratin. It usually appears as a firm, raised, yellowish-white lump on the skin typically found on the face, scalp, neck or upper extremities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlantar warts\u003C/strong\u003E are small, rough growths on the feet, caused by HPV. They can be painful, especially when pressure is applied to them, such as when standing or walking. They usually have a rough, grainy surface, can be dark and may have small black dots. The clinical appearance in this case does not support the diagnosis of plantar warts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmelanotic melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a form of melanoma in which the malignant cells have little to no pigment. Increasing age and sun exposure are two major risk factors for this condition. Typical early lesions present as asymmetrical macular lesions that may be uniformly pink or red and may have a faint light tan, brown, or grey pigmentation at the periphery. The borders may be well- or ill-defined.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma \u003C/strong\u003Eof the skin result from prolonged exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation. The initial presentation of SCC includes a history of a nonhealing ulcer or abnormal growth in a sun-exposed area. The position of the lesion does not make this the likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dermatofibroma is a common benign painless a firm, raised, reddish-brown fibrous nodule usually resulting from a trauma.","The \u0027dimple sign\u0027 is a characteristic feature of dermatofibroma, where the lesion dimples inward when pinched."],"references":["Parish LC, Yazdanian S, Lambert WC, Lambert PC. Dermatofibroma: a curious tumor. Skinmed. 2012 Sep-Oct;10(5):268-70. PMID: 23163067. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23163067/","Jung KD, Lee DY, Lee JH, Yang JM, Lee ES. Subcutaneous dermatofibroma. Ann Dermatol. 2011 May;23(2):254-7. doi: 10.5021/ad.2011.23.2.254. Epub 2011 May 27. PMID: 21747634; PMCID: PMC3130878. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3130878/","Myers DJ, Fillman EP. Dermatofibroma. [Updated 2024 Feb 29]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470538/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64491"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11698"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19664"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19664"},"attribut